URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1223660188	2023-03-27 14:21:38.333871	5882	species	avibase-0BFE075B	Diademed Sandpiper-Plover	Phegornis mitchellii				1					Chile	CL	Arica y Parinacota	CL-AP	Putre	CL-AP-PUT					PN Lauca--Las Cuevas	L572426	H	-18.1670566	-69.4337654	2005-11-11		obsr337436	S93684818	Historical	P62	EBIRD				1	0		0	1	1			Bird of the trip! The road at Embalse El Yeso was blocked by a landslide, and there were no birds this year at the usual spot at km 146 or near the football field of Parinacota, so we had to look for a new location.  The bog where we saw our DSP is very close to the traditional spot at km 146. To reach it, drive to km 146 and park at the Las Cuevas buildings. On the right hand side is the "traditional" DSP site, but as I said there were no DSPs there this year - perhaps the new-looking wooden suspension bridge and the big herd of vicuna's that was present have caused the DSPs to abandon the site.--Anyway, the bird we saw was on the left hand side of the road (coming from Putre). Look for a footpath marked with small white stones just opposite the Las Cuevas building. Walk across the hill, and you will notice that the path bends to the left as it goes downhill. Instead of going left, go straight onto the bofedal. The bird was right there, less than 100m away, where it was nesting just underneath an old and destroyed fence. We were wondering that the DSPs may do this deliberately, because the fence offers shelter for the many many vicuna's that roam the bofedales and pose a serious threat for the nests.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1221074986	2021-08-20 11:31:17.783673	5882	species	avibase-0BFE075B	Diademed Sandpiper-Plover	Phegornis mitchellii				3					Peru	PE	Junín	PE-JUN			PE_14790				Pampa Curicocha	L835214	H	-11.5607621	-76.2760162	1983-07-28		obsr135617	S93488494	Historical	P62	EBIRD				2	1	G7109980	0	1	0		Tom Schulenberg and I left Lima at 0430 and headed up the central highway. Our first stop was at a wet valley NW of Chinchan (this locality could not be located on maps/Google Earth -- presume the name may have changed; it was very close to the Lima/Junin dept. border). The valley in Junin, which was before the enormous glacial peak, at that time was referred to as Pampa Puracocha, elevation ca. 4600 m.  We stopped at the glacial lake just inside the Junin border, which apparently now is known as Laguna Lachis, before working further up that valley to below the above mentioned peak. Sky clear until ca. 1300.  We arrived back in Lima at ca. 1900.  Specimens deposited at LSU.
